# {{context|ambitransitive|lang=en}} To form letters, words or symbols on a surface in order to communicate.
#: {{usex|lang=en|The pupil '''wrote''' his name on the paper.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|Your son has been '''writing''' on the wall.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To be the author of (a book, article, poem, etc.).
#: {{usex|lang=en|My uncle '''writes''' newspaper articles for The Herald.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1893|author={{w|Walter Besant}}|title=[http://gutenberg.org/ebooks/34738 The Ivory Gate]|chapter=Prologue
|passage=Thus, when he drew up instructions in lawyer language{{...}}; his clerks, however, understood him very well. If he had '''written''' a love letter, or a farce, or a ''ballade'', or a story, no one, either clerks, or friends, or compositors, would have understood anything but a word here and a word there.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To send written information to.
#: {{usex|lang=en|(UK) Please '''write''' to me when you get there.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|(US) Please '''write''' me when you get there.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To show (information, etc) in written form.
#: {{usex|lang=en|The due day of the homework is '''written''' in the syllabus.}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To be an author.
#: {{usex|lang=en|I '''write''' for a living.}}
# {{context|transitive|computing|lang=en}} To record (data) mechanically or electronically.
#: {{usex|lang=en|The computer '''writes''' to the disk faster than it reads from it.}}
# {{context|transitive|South Africa|Canada|of a form, a document, etc.|lang=en}} To [[fill in]], to [[complete]] using words.
#: {{usex|lang=en|I was very anxious to know my score after I '''wrote''' the test.}}
# To impress durably; to imprint; to engrave.
#: {{usex|lang=en|truth '''written''' on the heart}}
# To make known by writing; to record; to prove by one's own written testimony; often used reflexively.
#* {{w|John Milton}} (1608-1674)
#*: He who '''writes''' himself by his own inscription is like an ill painter, who, by writing on a shapeless picture which he hath drawn, is fain to tell passengers what shape it is, which else no man could imagine.

